            <biogHist>
                <p>James Campbell was born to John Campbell, crofter, and Mary Campbell n√©e Burk. In
                    1841 he was living in Gleann with his wife Chirsty and six children: Antony
                    (14), Mary (12), Donald (7), Marion (9), Pol (5) and John (3). Originally a
                    crofter, but had moved to Tradespark, Nairn, by the 1851 Census, and was working
                    as a road labourer along with his son Antony. His wife was with them together
                    with four of their children: Sally [Mary], Donald, Paul and a daughter Erick,
                    aged 6. By 1861 they had moved back to Barra and were living at Tangusdale
                    [Tangasdale] and James had returned to crofting. Only three children were living
                    with now, Marion, Donald and Euphemia (16). By 1871 James was living with his
                    wife at Kentangaval, and occupied as a fisherman. They had a lodger Flora
                    McTagart, who may have been the wife of Chirsty's brother Roderick. Flora was 76
                    years old, a pauper, and classed as an imbecile. </p>
                <p>James Campbell died in June 1876 from chronic bronchitis and asthma which had
                    lasted six months. His son Donald signed the certificate. Chirsty died three
                    years later on 11 November 1879 after suffering a year of chronic bronchitis.
                    Her daughter Effy (Euphemia) McKinnon signed the certificate.</p>
